# Perl style

## Pragmas & safety

* Always include `use strict;` and `use warnings;` at the top of every file.
* Never use global variables unless explicitly forced by a framework; favor `my` lexical scoping.

## Layout & formatting

* **Indentation**: Use exactly 4 spaces per indentation level. Do not use hard tabs.
* **Braces**: Use the "cuddled else" style. Put the opening brace on the same line as the keyword, and the closing brace on its own line matching the start keyword column.
* **Line length**: Keep lines between 120–150 characters whenever possible. Broken lines must split after an operator.
* **Trailing whitespace**: Do not leave spaces or tabs at the end of a line. Trim trailing whitespace on every line you edit or add (including blank lines — they must be truly empty).
* **Spacing**: One space before the opening brace of a multi-line block. No space between a function name and its opening parenthesis. Space after every comma.

```perl
# GOOD — cuddled else
if ($ok) {
    do_work();
} else {
    handle_error();
}

# BAD — opening brace on its own line
if ($ok)
{
    do_work();
}

# GOOD — break after operator
my $total = $long_variable_name + $another_long_name
    + $third_part;

# GOOD — no space before '(' on calls; space after commas
do_something($arg1, $arg2);

# BAD
do_something ($arg1, $arg2);

# GOOD — one space before '{' on multi-line blocks
sub process_data {
    ...
}

foreach my $item (@items) {
    ...
}

# BAD — no space before '{' on multi-line blocks
sub process_data{
    ...
}

foreach my $item (@items){
    ...
}
```

## Subroutines

* Never use subroutine prototypes (`sub name ($$)`) as they are largely broken for general use.
* Always unpack parameters from `@_` immediately at the top of the subroutine using `my ( $var1, $var2 ) = @_;`.
* Prefer named parameters (passing a hash reference) if a subroutine accepts more than two parameters. The preferred name for the argument is `$args`. When editing code assume this practice has already been followed if the first unpacked argument is `$args`.
* Prefer an explicit `return` statement; do not rely on implicit last-evaluated expression returns.

## References & dereferencing

When a scalar holds an **array ref** or **hash ref**, always dereference with `->`. Do not use the legacy/bracket form on the scalar itself.

```perl
# BAD — ambiguous; looks like a plain array subscript
my $first = $sites_sorted[0];
my $slice = $items[1 .. 3];

# GOOD
my $first = $sites_sorted->[0];
my $slice = $items->[1 .. 3];
```

Prefer storing refs in scalars (`my $items = [...]`) and iterating with `@$items` or `$items->[$i]`.

```perl
# BAD
my $name = $user{name};
my $bad  = @$resp{qw(code message)};      # avoid — use braces + arrow context
my $val  = $self->method->{'key1'}{'key2'};

# GOOD
my $name = $user->{'name'};
my @pair = @{$resp}{qw(code message)};
my $pair = {%{$resp}{qw(code message)}};
my $val  = $self->method->{'key1'}->{'key2'};
```

Plain arrays and hashes (not refs) use normal subscripting:

```perl
my $first = $sites[0];      # ok — @sites is a real array
my $val   = $meta{key};     # ok — %meta is a real hash
```

When editing: if you introduce or touch a ref, use `->` for element/key access. When converting `@name` to `$name = [...]`, update all subscripts to `$name->[...]` and list context to `@$name`.

When chaining hash key access on references (including a method return value), put `->` before **every** `{...}` after the first dereference. Do not omit the arrow between consecutive hash keys.

```perl
# BAD — missing -> between hash keys
$self->method->{'key1'}{'key2'};
$self->strata->local_cache($TOPIC)->{'auth_token'}{$brand};
$obj->response->{'data'}{'status'};

# GOOD
$self->method->{'key1'}->{'key2'};
$self->strata->local_cache($TOPIC)->{'auth_token'}->{$brand};
$obj->response->{'data'}->{'status'};
```

## Hash & named-arg alignment

When writing hashes or named-argument lists with **two or more keys on separate lines**, align `=>` in a single column.

* Pad each key with spaces so `=>` begins **one space after the longest key name** in that block (longest key length + 1 space, then `=>`).
* Align within one hash/list block only (do not chase alignment across unrelated blocks).
* Apply to hash refs, method args, `return` lists, and option hashes.
* Single-line hashes do not need alignment.

```perl
# BAD — ragged =>
my $resp = $obj->method({
    key1       => 'value1',
    key2       => 'value2',
    key3 => undef,
    key4 => {key1 => 'value4'},
});

# GOOD — longest key is key_long (8); one space after each padded key, then =>
my $resp = $obj->method({
    key1     => 'value1',
    key2     => 'value2',
    key3     => undef,
    key4     => {key1 => 'value4'},
    key_long => 'value5',
    key6     => 'value6',
});
```

```perl
# GOOD — return / option defaults (longest key: hours, 5 chars)
return (
    hours => 5,
    fork  => 10,
);

# longest key: really_long_key_name, 20 chars
return {
    really_long_key_name => $row->{'id'},
    logs                 => \@logs,
    summary              => \%summary,
};
```

Align inner blocks separately when they have multiple keys:

```perl
key4 => {key1 => 'value4'},
```

When adding or changing a key in an aligned block, re-align the whole block.

## Modern idioms

* Avoid using the implicit global variable `$_` except inside short map, grep, or structural blocks.
* Prefer `if ... elsif ... else` blocks over repeating standalone `if` statements checking the same variable context.
* Use the three-argument form of `open` (e.g., `open(my $fh, '<', $filename)`) combined with lexical filehandles and explicit error handling via `$!`.
* Prefer `throw` over `die` when the file already imports a throwing helper (`use Throw;` or `use GT::Throw;`). Otherwise use `die`.

## POD

* Use the standard Plain Old Documentation (POD) format for modules.
* If present, place `=head1 NAME`, then `=head1 SYNOPSIS`, then `=head1 DESCRIPTION` at the top of the file (after `use` lines), in that order.
* All other POD (`=head1` sections and below) goes after the functional code.
* Always initiate POD headers with `=encoding utf8` and format primary `=head1` tags in uppercase.
